explanation:
OS_CHECK_POINTER, OS_CHECK_SIZE: macros used at function entry — their definitions may contain code (including for-loops) or side effects relevant to MISRA for-loop analysis.

OS_ObjectIdGetById: called by OS_QueuePut; any for-loops in this function or its callees would contribute to the behaviour of OS_QueuePut and must be inspected.

OS_ObjectIdTransactionInit, OS_ObjectIdToArrayIndex, OS_ObjectIdConvertToken, OS_ObjectIdTransactionCancel: direct callees (or helpers) used by OS_ObjectIdGetById — include to allow inspection for any for-loops or modifications to loop counters/objects.

OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET: macro used to obtain the queue pointer; its expansion may contain expressions or loops that affect compliance.

OS_queue_table: the global table macro/indexing operates on — needed to see how OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET accesses data and whether that access participates in any for-loop semantics.

OS_queue_internal_record_t: type of *queue; needed to check fields (e.g., max_size) and whether accessing them involves side effects or hidden loops.

OS_object_token_t: token type passed to OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET and OS_QueuePut_Impl — its definition/semantics may influence whether objects used in loop clauses are modified.

OS_QUEUE_INVALID_SIZE, OS_SUCCESS: status constants used by control flow — included to understand return paths that may avoid or enter code containing loops.

OS_QueuePut_Impl: called when sizes are OK; its body must be inspected for any for-loops (and for whether those loops obey the MISRA constraints). Its behaviour is part of the overall function behaviour.

OS_ObjectIndexFromToken: called (directly or indirectly) by OS_QueuePut_Impl per the call graph — include to inspect for-loops or side effects that would count toward MISRA analysis.

OS_LOCK_MODE_NONE, LOCAL_OBJID_TYPE: arguments to OS_ObjectIdGetById; include to understand object-lookup semantics which could affect whether shared objects used in loop clauses are modified elsewhere.

OS_printf: referenced by macros/call graph; include because macros or helpers invoked during checks may call OS_printf (or similar) and those helpers might contain loops or side effects relevant to the rule.

Rationale: The MISRA rule concerns well-formed for-loops including effects of functions called from loop bodies. Although OS_QueuePut itself has no for-loop, any functions or macros it invokes (or their callees) may contain for-loops whose behaviour contributes to the overall compliance. The listed symbols cover all macros, types, globals, functions, and helper routines directly used by OS_QueuePut and its immediate callees so the next analyst can inspect their definitions for for-loops and side-effects relevant to the rule.
